DataSpace Project : Absenteeism at work¶

Gaetano Ferrara s254904¶

The main purpose of this report is to analyse the dataset "Absenteeism at work Data Set", downloadable from UCI Machine Learning (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Absenteeism+at+work). Every record contains many different features that describe personal characteristics of the individual. The objective is to predict if a given employee make no_absenteeism or absenteeism . This is possible thanks to the prediction of an index named "Absenteeism time in hours" that show number of absenteeism.

Correlation Matrix¶

Here we can see the Heatmap Correlation Plot, means an heatmap that represent the value of correlation measured for each couple of feature of our dataset. Obviously, the upper-right part is equally to the lower-left one, splitted by the "1" diagonal that is the correlation of each feature with itself.

Correlation is a statistical term which in common usage refers to how close two variables are to having a linear relationship with each other. For example, two variables which are linearly dependent (say, x and y which depend on each other as x = 2y) will have a higher correlation than two variables which are non-linearly dependent (say, u and v which depend on each other as u = v2).¶

Specifically, Pearson Correlation is defined as:

da sistemare ----$$ Cor(X,Y)=∑ni=1(xi−x)(yi−y¯¯¯)∑ni=1(xi−x¯¯¯)2√∑ni=1(yi−y¯¯¯)2√ $$

The values of the correlation coefficient can range from -1 to +1. The closer it is to +1 or -1, the more closely are the two variables are related. The positive sign signifies the direction of the correlation i.e. if one of the variables increases, the other variable is also supposed to increase, otherwise if the sign is negative, the trend is opposite.

Features with high correlation are more linearly dependent and hence have almost the same effect on the dependent variable. So, when two features have high correlation, eventually we can drop one of the two features. Meanwhile, looking at the class choosen for classification, the correlated features will be the ones more usefull for our estimator, so it is a way to display the importance of a determinated predictor knowing the prediction goal.

Heatmap above give us the possibility to deeply understand correlation between variables: it is so important to understand if two variable are strongly correlated, because their contribute to classification is strongly bounded, and we can keep just one of two of these without loosing too accuracy for the model .in this case we can see that exist a strong correlation between weight,height and body mass index. This positvie strong correlation is normal because

$$ Body mass index = (weight)/(height * (costant)) $$

then for the classification we can pick to remove height and weight without loosing too accuracy for the model.

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
# calculate the principal components
pca = PCA()
df_pca = pca.fit_transform(scaled_df)

tot = sum(pca.explained_variance_)
var_exp = [(i / tot)*100 for i in sorted(pca.explained_variance_, reverse=True)]
cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(var_exp)

trace1 = dict(
    type='bar',
    x=['PC %s' %(i+1) for i in range(20)],
    y=var_exp,
    name='Individual'
)

trace2 = dict(
    type='scatter',
    x=['PC %s' %(i+1) for i in range(20)], 
    y=cum_var_exp,
    name='Cumulative'
)

data = [trace1, trace2]

layout=dict(
    title='Explained variance by different principal components',
    yaxis=dict(
        title='Explained variance in percent'
    ),
    annotations=list([
        dict(
            x=1.16,
            y=1.05,
            xref='paper',
            yref='paper',
            text='Explained Variance',
            showarrow=False,
        )
    ])
)

fig = dict(data=data, layout=layout)
iplot(fig, filename='selecting-principal-components')

Graph's function¶

In this section I will provide all the function's declarations, used for classification procedure.

  1. plot_learning_curve function : given a set of parameters, such as estimator to be represented or train sizes for learning phases, it represent the evolution of learning stage in a two curves-based graph.

  2. cross_validation function : function that made the GridSearch for the classifier (and with the setup parameters) and return the best estimator based on the Accuracy scores.

  3. score_model function : helpful function that plot different statistics about the estimator such as time spent for both training and test and Accuracy and LogLoss score.

  4. plot_confusion_matrix function : allow to compute and display the confusion matrix for a given estimator and a given dataset.

In [21]:
def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None,
                        n_jobs=None, train_sizes=np.linspace(.01, 1.0, 50)):
   
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
    plt.title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    plt.ylabel("Score")
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    plt.grid()

    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="g")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g",
             label="Cross-validation score")

    plt.legend(loc="best")
    return plt



def cross_validation(clf, clf_params,X,y):
    start = time.time()
    best_clf = GridSearchCV(estimator=clf,param_grid=clf_params, cv=5,scoring='accuracy', return_train_score=True)
    best_clf.fit(X,y)
    end = time.time()
    print("Accuracy for result of cross validation:",best_clf.best_score_)
    print("Cross validation requires:",end-start,"sec")
    return best_clf.best_estimator_




def score_model(clf,X,y,name):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size = TestSize,random_state=Seed1)
    start_tr = time.time()
    clf.fit(X_train,y_train)
    training_time=time.time()-start_tr
    start_te = time.time()
    predictions = clf.predict_proba(X)
    lloss=metrics.log_loss(y_true=y,y_pred=predictions,labels=[0,1])
    accuracy=clf.score(X_test,y_test)
    test_time = time.time()-start_te
    score_res = []
    score_res.append(("Name",name))
    score_res.append(("Accuracy",accuracy))
    score_res.append(("Log Loss",lloss))
    score_res.append(("Training Time",training_time))
    score_res.append(("Test Time",test_time))
    print("Scores:")
    for name,result in score_res:
        print(name,"=",result)
    return score_res



def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title=None,
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if not title:
        if normalize:
            title = 'Normalized confusion matrix'
        else:
            title = 'Confusion matrix, without normalization'

    # Compute confusion matrix
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    # Only use the labels that appear in the data
   # classes = classes[unique_labels(y_true, y_pred)]
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    print(cm)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    im = ax.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    ax.figure.colorbar(im, ax=ax)
    # We want to show all ticks...
    ax.set(xticks=np.arange(cm.shape[1]),
           yticks=np.arange(cm.shape[0]),
           # ... and label them with the respective list entries
           xticklabels=classes, yticklabels=classes,
           title=title,
           ylabel='True label',
           xlabel='Predicted label')

    # Rotate the tick labels and set their alignment.
    plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right",
             rotation_mode="anchor")

    # Loop over data dimensions and create text annotations.
    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i in range(cm.shape[0]):
        for j in range(cm.shape[1]):
            ax.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                    ha="center", va="center",
                    color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")
    fig.tight_layout()
    return ax



def normalize(X):
    npX = np.asarray(X)
    npX = preprocessing.StandardScaler(copy=True,with_mean=True,with_std=True).fit_transform(npX) #Normalization
    return pandas.DataFrame(npX)

Feature Importance¶

feature importance is a method provided by Random Forest to describe how features affects the classification in the Decision trees ensemble. So it is a first indicator of how much feature are relevant in classification and how much are quite useless. That's becouse evaluate ensemble methods is so difficult: for this reason, it is provided an overall summary of the importance of each predictor (using the cumulative decrement of Gini Index).
